1
00:00:00,160 --> 00:00:05,440
Order in the court! An insurance policy isn't just a basic corporate receipt.

2
00:00:05,440 --> 00:00:18,880
It is a formal contract defined under article 305 of the new civil code as a meeting of minds where one party binds himself to give something or render a service.

3
00:00:18,880 --> 00:00:25,439
To be legally enforcable, an agreement must stand on four essential elements.

4
00:00:25,439 --> 00:00:31,439
One, agreement consisting of a clear offer by one party and an explicit acceptance by the other.

5
00:00:31,439 --> 00:00:43,520
Two, competent parties. The insurer must hold a valid license to do business and the insured cannot be a minor, mentally incompetent, or a defined public enemy.

6
00:00:43,520 --> 00:00:52,160
Three, legal purpose. The contract cannot run contrary to law, morals, or public interest.

7
00:00:52,160 --> 00:00:56,960
Four, consideration. the premium payment value exchanged for the assumption of loss.

8
00:00:56,960 --> 00:01:04,159
If an agreement violates these pillars, it drops into one of four defective categories.

9
00:01:04,159 --> 00:01:12,799
Reissible contracts are technically valid but can be legally set aside because they cause distinct economic damage or involve concealment or misrepresentation.

10
00:01:12,799 --> 00:01:20,720
Voidable contracts appear valid on the surface but hold a structural legal flaw like an agreement signed by a minor.

11
00:01:20,720 --> 00:01:30,960
Uninforcable contracts occur when an individual executes an agreement completely lacking the legal authority to do so.

12
00:01:30,960 --> 00:01:44,799
Void or inexistent contracts have a purpose completely contrary to law, morals, or public policy, like a contract protecting an illegal drug supply. They have zero lawful objective and are void from day one.

13
00:01:44,799 --> 00:01:58,079
Section two of the new insurance code formally defines our subject as an agreement to indemnify another against loss, damage, or liability arising from an unknown or contingent event.

14
00:01:58,079 --> 00:02:05,920
When you open up a physical insurance policy, you will find six standard highly structured components.

15
00:02:05,920 --> 00:02:13,040
First is the preamble, which states the core purpose of the contract, identifies the two parties, and declares that the premium must be fully paid.

16
00:02:13,040 --> 00:02:25,920
Second is the insuring clause also known as the operative clause which outlines the insurer's formal agreement to pay if the loss occurs during the period of insurance due to a covered peril.

17
00:02:25,920 --> 00:02:33,599
Third is the attestation clause which officially confirms that the insurer has authenticated the policy by signature.

18
00:02:33,599 --> 00:02:44,239
Fourth is the policy schedule which logs all user specific metrics like your name, address, terms, premium rates and the description or location of the risk.

19
00:02:44,239 --> 00:02:52,480
Fifth are the conditions defining the strict operational rights, exclusions and claim duties of both parties.

20
00:02:52,480 --> 00:03:02,319
And sixth are endorsements which are separate attached documents used to modify the base policy's original terms, conditions, or scope.

21
00:03:02,319 --> 00:03:15,120
Oh, and keep an eye out for a cover note. These are crucial temporary contracts issued to provide coverage for a maximum period of 60 days pending the formal issuance of the final policy document.

22
00:03:15,120 --> 00:03:20,480
When a legal dispute over text language arises, courts use strict rules of construction.

23
00:03:20,480 --> 00:03:30,400
Phrasiology must be interpreted based on its plain, ordinary, and popular sense, though strict technical meanings are applied to technical terms.

24
00:03:30,400 --> 00:03:42,080
If a clause is genuinely ambiguous, it is always construed strictly against the insurer and liberally in favor of the insured because the client had zero say in writing the text.

25
00:03:42,080 --> 00:03:52,000
And if the preprinted terms contradict a handwritten or typed edition, the written portion always wins because it captures the true immediate intention of the contract.

26
00:03:52,000 --> 00:03:57,519
This is because insurance contracts possess unique structural qualities.

27
00:03:57,519 --> 00:04:05,360
They are aliatory meaning the outcome hinges entirely on chance or an uncertain event.

28
00:04:05,360 --> 00:04:09,920
They are contracts of adhesion because the insured must accept the text as written by the company.

29
00:04:09,920 --> 00:04:17,280
They are personal meaning the contract is tied explicitly to the specific character and credit of the owner.

30
00:04:17,280 --> 00:04:22,320
If ownership of the property changes, the insurance does not automatically pass to the new owner.

31
00:04:22,320 --> 00:04:31,120
They are unilateral, meaning only the insurer makes a legally enforcable promise to pay for losses after the premium is received.

32
00:04:31,120 --> 00:04:38,639
And they are conditional because the insured must satisfy specific requirements before collecting a dime.

33
00:04:38,639 --> 00:04:50,320
Finally, let's step up to the bench and look at the six general principles of insurance that govern every single claim evaluation.

34
00:04:50,320 --> 00:05:01,600
Principle one is utmost good faith. Both parties must completely disclose all material facts that would influence risk decisions or premium pricing.

35
00:05:01,600 --> 00:05:12,479
Breaking this via concealment, neglecting to communicate a material fact or misrepresentation where facts failed to match assertions renders the contract resessible.

36
00:05:12,479 --> 00:05:25,199
Principle two is insurable interest. You must have a legal relation to the subject matter such that you suffer financially if it is damaged and benefit from its safety.

37
00:05:25,199 --> 00:05:36,320
For property insurance, this interest must exist when the insurance takes effect and when the loss occurs. For life insurance, it must exist only when the insurance takes effect.

38
00:05:36,320 --> 00:05:50,240
Principle three is indemnity. This ensures an insured is compensated for actual losses sustained and placed back into the exact same financial position occupied right before the disaster.

39
00:05:50,240 --> 00:05:58,720
You are never allowed to profit from insurance. Life and personal accident insurance are the explicit exceptions here.

40
00:05:58,720 --> 00:06:08,880
Indemnity can be delivered via monetary payment, reinstatement, repair min or article replacement.

41
00:06:08,880 --> 00:06:13,199
Principle four is subregation. A direct corlary to indemnity.

42
00:06:13,199 --> 00:06:25,280
It allows the insurer to stand in the shoes of the insured and pursue legal remedies or third-party recoveries against a negligent party who caused the accident, but only up to the exact amount paid out on the claim.

43
00:06:25,280 --> 00:06:31,360
This prevents the insured from recovering twice and profiting.

44
00:06:31,360 --> 00:06:39,440
Principle five is contribution. This applies when there is double insurance, meaning multiple policies cover the same interest, matter, and peril.

45
00:06:39,440 --> 00:06:41,919
Insurers pay proportionately to the loss.

46
00:06:41,919 --> 00:06:58,319
If a policy carries a standard contribution clause, the insured losses the power to arbitrarily pick one company to pay the whole amount. All insurers pay their ratable proportion.

47
00:06:58,319 --> 00:07:09,919
Principle six is proximate cause. This is the active efficient cause that sets a seamless chain of events in motion, bringing about a loss without the intervention of any force started from a new independent source.

48
00:07:09,919 --> 00:07:18,080
Proximity is judged entirely by its operational effectiveness, not by which event was closest in time to the accident.

49
00:07:18,080 --> 00:07:34,560
All of these parameters are governed by Republic Act number 10,67, otherwise known as the Insurance Code of 2013, which gives the insurance commissioner full authority to regulate companies, agents, and brokers alike.

50
00:07:34,560 --> 00:07:39,199
That wraps up our masterclass text transcript for module 1.

51
00:07:39,199 --> 00:07:49,599
